if you import another module from a component and don't provide a path, it should base the path on the root of the Resources directory, ie:
```typescript
import * as myModule from "Scripts/mymodule";
```

should find that file at ```<game project>/Resources/mymodule.ts```
However, the TypeScript compiler complains that the file cannot be found.

If you do the same in vanilla js, it works
```javascript
var mymodule = require("Scripts/mymodule");
```

The routines that setup and invoke the TypeScript compiler need to be able to handle this situation.  The workaround is to specify relative paths, such as:
```typescript
import * as myModule from "./mymodule";
//or
import * as myModule from "../Modules/mymodule";
```

TypeScript has the ability to have enums and with a compiler flag, the generated ```js``` will automatically be replaced with the constant ```int``` value when transpiled.  

so in ```Atomic.d.ts``` you would have
```
  export const enum CurveType {
      INSTANT = 0,
      LINEAR = 1,
      QUADRATIC = 2,
      CUBIC = 3
  }
```
instead of
```
   export type CurveType = number;
   export var INSTANT: CurveType;
   export var LINEAR: CurveType;
   export var QUADRATIC: CurveType;
   export var CUBIC: CurveType;
```

Two issues may crop up when migrating to this:
* The generated ```js``` code would have these variables replaced with ```ints``` so the js will be slightly less readable, however a comment will be added that indicates the name of the enum.
* development in vanilla js would not be able to use the enums.  The internal enum name would need to be used so instead of using ```CurveType.INSTANT```, you would need to use ```Atomic.INSTANT```

The pro side to this though is that intellisense and readability in TypeScript scripts/components will be improved.
